				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Consider these two instructions:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; ldx #$17<br />&nbsp; lda $3FF0,x<br /></div><br />This takes seven cycles:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Read LDX #ii opcode </li><li>Read $17 operand </li><li>Read LDA aaaa,X opcode </li><li>Read address low byte $F0 </li><li>Read address high byte $3F. (In the background, the 6502 is adding $F0 to $17 to produce the low byte of the effective address, which is $07.) </li><li>Read $3F07. (In the background, the 6502 is adding the carry to $3F to produce $40.) </li><li>Notice there was a carry and try again reading $4007 </li></ol><br />Cycle 6 reads $3F07, which on the NES is a mirror of $2007, the PPU VRAM data port. This puts the current value in the VRAM read buffer on the CPU's data bus, reads from the current VRAM address, puts that in the read buffer, and adds 1 or 32 to the VRAM address.<br /><br />Cycle 7 reads $4007, which isn't connected to anything on the NES. (For writing, it's the square 1 high period, but it doesn't respond to reads.) This &quot;open bus&quot; situation means that the inherent capacitance of the data bus will cause the previous value to remain on the bus. And in this case, the previous value is that from $3F07 == $2007 == data read from VRAM.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

